>In article <27tr36$qda@news.delphi.com>, anspring@news.delphi.com (ANSPRING@DELPHI.COM) writes:
>> I've head it mentioned (in sci.crypt, I think) that DES is highly
>> resistant to differential cryptanalysis, because of the design of the S-Boxes.
>> Since DES was introduced in ... I forget .. late 70's?  and the NSA advised
>> IBM on its design, we can guess that NSA know about DiffCrypt 10 years
>> before it became commonly known.

>Don Coppersmith of IBM has stated, both on the net and in a draft
>paper, that IBM developed differential cryptanalysis on its own 18
>years before Biham and Shamir rediscovered it.  Why finger NSA?

Wasn't it also stated, though, that "IBM rediscovered some of NSA's deepest 
secrets"?  This indicates that the NSA knew about differential cryptanalysis 
even before the IBM researchers did.  The NSA also claim to have discovered 
PKC's in the early '70's....
 
